From above, following general trends are observed (with exception of outliers / data noise)

  • Age is combined reflection of time taken to complete education and years of professional experience
  • Experience is proportional to age (subject to completion of education). For example, someone with 1 year of experience is aged higher, if they had taken time to get a higher degree of education
  • Similarly, income is in proportion to experience (subject to level of education). Someone with 1 year of experience gets a high income, if they are highly qualified on basis of education

Since these agree with general trends, we can say it is safe to assume that negative sign of experience is a typographical error and converting them to positive value can lead to sensible data

Pairplot shows that

  1. Age and Experience have a strong, linear correlation to one another, but it does not affect the possibility of customer taking Personal Loan

  2. Income is one of the key attributes which decides customer taking a personal loan. Customers having annual income more than 100k dollars are more likely to avail personal loan. Further, age and experience dont have correlation on income. As income increases, there is scope for customers to have higher CC Avg spending per month

  3. Customers who have purchasing power of 3k dollars (CC Avg.) per month or above, also have income equal to or above 100k dollars. So, income influences more than CCAvg spending per month for a customer to avail personal loan

  4. Highest value of Mortgage is having a correlation with increasing Income. However,
